                            <handDesc>
                                <handNote xml:id="hand-1">
                                    <locus from="2r" to="49v" scheme="folios"/>Gothic semihybrida. Scribe: <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102781">Nils Jakobsson Byrkop</persName>. </handNote>
                                <handNote xml:id="hand-2">
                                    <locus from="50r" to="53r" scheme="folios"/>Hybrida. </handNote>
                            </handDesc>
                            <additions>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>The enitre page is covered in pen-trials by the scribe. For more on the additions here and on 53v, see <bibl>
                                            <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/101007">Maliniemi (1957)</title>
                                            <citedRange from="20" to="20" unit="page"/>
                                        </bibl>.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="1v" to="1v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Upper part of page, in bronw ink by a medieval hand: a fragmented prayer; middle of page, in ink by an early modern hand: <quote>Lectiones historia de sanctis Regni Sueciae Martyribus et patronis olim in Ecclesiis Suecanis usitate</quote>.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="2r" to="53r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Additions in the margins by one or serveral contemporary hands, e.g. on <locus from="7v" to="7v" scheme="folios"/> or <locus from="19r" to="19r" scheme="folios"/>.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="3r" to="3r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Upper right corner, in ink by a modern hand: <quote>Scr. Rer. Suec. II.</quote> (text indentification)</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="53v" to="53v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Four different texts by the same hand, the first two are written in a faded ink. Text 1 carrries the title <quote>Contra pulices</quote>; text 2 is 10 line long poem beginning: <quote>O doctor moris</quote>; text 3 is in Swedish and seems to be a recipe against ringworm (<quote>raefform</quote>); text 4 has the title: <quote>De decimis et oblacionibus</quote>. </note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="54r" to="54r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>A text in Swedish, but the leaf is damaged and the ink faded. It seems to be related to <bibl>
                                            <title ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/102913">Läke- och örteböcker från Sveriges medeltid</title>
                                            <citedRange from="208" to="208" unit="page"/>
                                        </bibl>.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="54v" to="54v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Unindentified text, possibly a recipe. </note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="Stub_A" to="Stub_B" scheme="other"/>
                                    <note>A few words or parts of words can be seen on the stubs. They seem to be written by the same hand as the other additions. </note>
                                </p>
                            </additions>
                            <decoDesc>
                                <p>Main text in brown ink, rubrics in red (green on <locus from="46r" to="47v" scheme="folios"/>), capitals touched in red. </p>
